There is a lowering bug when casting constant tensor values. The bug causes the program to halt at `CastOpConversion::matchAndRewrite` which is within `convert-tile-to-pxa`.

Here's an example of a C++ EDSL program that triggers the bug:

```
auto O = cast(Tensor{3}, DType::FLOAT32);
```

Here's the tile code which runs into this bug.

```
module {
  func @const_cast() -> tensor<f32> {
    %c3 = "eltwise.sconst"() {value = 3 : i64} : () -> tensor<si32>
    %0 = "eltwise.cast"(%c3) : (tensor<si32>) -> tensor<f32>
    return %0 : tensor<f32>
  }
}
```

The bug also exists if you cast a constant to its own existing datatype (we have a folder for that scenario now, though).

When I'm trying to get a bitwise not of a Tensor like this
```cpp
std::vector<int64_t> I_shape{1, 3, 16, 16};
auto I = Placeholder(DType::INT16, I_shape);
auto O = -I;
auto program = ProgramBuilder("tensor_neg", {O}).intx(DType::INT16).compile();
```
It gets compile error:

error: failed to legalize operation 'eltwise.neg'
terminate called after throwing an instance of 'std::runtime_error'
  what():  conversion to the LLVM IR dialect failed

Instead, We have to use `auto O = 0 - I;` , which could get the same result.

When I'm trying to get a bitwise not of a Tensor like this
```cpp
std::vector<int64_t> I_shape{1, 3, 16, 16};
auto I = Placeholder(DType::FLOAT16, I_shape);
auto O = ~I;
auto program = ProgramBuilder("tensor_round", {O}).floatx(DType::FLOAT16).compile();
```
It gets compile error:

error: failed to legalize operation 'eltwise.bit_not'
terminate called after throwing an instance of 'std::runtime_error'
  what():  conversion to the LLVM IR dialect failed
 
It seems it's not well supported.

In a very simple tile example, such like below:    
 
    auto order = mv::Order("NCHW");
    std::vector<int64_t> I_shape{1, 1, 16, 16};
    auto I = Placeholder(DType::FLOAT16, I_shape);
    auto B = I * 1.5;
    auto R = plaidml::op::concatenate({I, B}, 2);
    auto program = ProgramBuilder("test_concatenate", {R}) 
                       .floatx(DType::FLOAT16)
                       .compile();

we will get the compile **error**:

**error: 'affine.store' op first operand must have same type memref element type**
terminate called after throwing an instance of 'std::runtime_error'
  what():  conversion to the LLVM IR dialect failed

but if we cast tensor(B) to DType::FLOAT16, then it would compile successfully.

   `auto B = cast( I * 1.5, DType::FLOAT16);`

because the ProgramBuilder::floatx() method is used for specifying which data type constants will actually have. 
since we already set it to FLOAT16. why we still need to cast tensor(B)?

